WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:08.809 align:middle line:90%
[ Music ]

00:00:09.777 --> 00:00:11.812 align:middle line:84%
>> Hello, my delicious
co-creators.

00:00:11.812 --> 00:00:13.614 align:middle line:90%
Lilou here for Gaiam TV.

00:00:13.614 --> 00:00:15.182 align:middle line:90%
Today, I'm in the Netherlands

00:00:15.182 --> 00:00:18.919 align:middle line:84%
in beautiful sunny Amsterdam
springtime here with Pim.

00:00:18.919 --> 00:00:20.421 align:middle line:90%
Hello.

00:00:20.421 --> 00:00:21.922 align:middle line:90%
>> Hello.

00:00:21.922 --> 00:00:23.424 align:middle line:84%
>> Really good sitting
next to you.

00:00:23.424 --> 00:00:25.392 align:middle line:84%
I've heard so many beautiful
things about your story.

00:00:25.392 --> 00:00:27.361 align:middle line:84%
I'm really excited
to share it with you.

00:00:27.361 --> 00:00:29.497 align:middle line:90%
Pim is a cardiologist-scientist

00:00:29.497 --> 00:00:32.199 align:middle line:84%
and he'd been really
looking very deep

00:00:32.199 --> 00:00:34.235 align:middle line:90%
into the near-death experiences.

00:00:34.235 --> 00:00:37.571 align:middle line:84%
I'm really thrilled to talk
to you about this topic

00:00:37.571 --> 00:00:41.142 align:middle line:84%
and discover more because
it's still such a--

00:00:41.142 --> 00:00:44.512 align:middle line:84%
not a new phenomenon but
something that you're going

00:00:44.512 --> 00:00:46.947 align:middle line:84%
to tell us is more and
more explained by science.

00:00:46.947 --> 00:00:49.850 align:middle line:84%
You wrote many books
and journals,

00:00:49.850 --> 00:00:51.352 align:middle line:90%
medical journals as well.

00:00:51.352 --> 00:00:52.853 align:middle line:84%
But this one was
your English one,

00:00:52.853 --> 00:00:55.489 align:middle line:90%
"Consciousness Beyond Life".

00:00:55.489 --> 00:00:58.459 align:middle line:84%
So, wow, where do we
start in all this?

00:00:58.459 --> 00:01:02.229 align:middle line:84%
Because I'm really-- tell us
about when you first heard

00:01:02.229 --> 00:01:04.331 align:middle line:90%
of near-death experience.

00:01:04.331 --> 00:01:06.433 align:middle line:90%
>> That's an interesting story.

00:01:06.433 --> 00:01:13.307 align:middle line:84%
That was in '69 just starting
my training in cardiology,

00:01:13.307 --> 00:01:15.743 align:middle line:90%
and then I was working

00:01:15.743 --> 00:01:19.980 align:middle line:84%
in a hospital [inaudible]
Coronary Care Unit

00:01:19.980 --> 00:01:21.882 align:middle line:90%
in Holland had started.

00:01:21.882 --> 00:01:28.923 align:middle line:84%
We always forget that 45 years
ago, in '67 before that time,

00:01:28.923 --> 00:01:31.559 align:middle line:84%
everybody died because of
cardiac arrest because a lot

00:01:31.559 --> 00:01:34.728 align:middle line:84%
of resuscitation techniques
like defibrillation

00:01:34.728 --> 00:01:37.331 align:middle line:84%
or external chest
massage were not possible.

00:01:37.331 --> 00:01:41.534 align:middle line:84%
So it was all new,
resuscitation, CPR.

00:01:41.534 --> 00:01:46.373 align:middle line:84%
So in '69, we had a
patient, 44 years old,

00:01:46.373 --> 00:01:49.443 align:middle line:84%
who had a cardiac arrest and
we started to resuscitate him

00:01:49.443 --> 00:01:54.281 align:middle line:84%
and we succeeded after several
defibrillations to get him back.

00:01:54.281 --> 00:01:58.152 align:middle line:84%
We-- resuscitated him and
we were very, very happy.

00:01:58.152 --> 00:02:01.689 align:middle line:84%
But the patient was
extremely disappointed.

00:02:01.689 --> 00:02:05.359 align:middle line:84%
And he told me about gong
to eternal, seeing a light,

00:02:05.359 --> 00:02:09.163 align:middle line:84%
seeing beautiful landscapes,
hearing beautiful music

00:02:09.163 --> 00:02:12.933 align:middle line:84%
and I didn't do anything with
it but I didn't forget it at all

00:02:12.933 --> 00:02:17.504 align:middle line:84%
and I didn't know that this kind
of experience had been mentioned

00:02:17.504 --> 00:02:20.874 align:middle line:84%
in old times, in all
cultures, and also religion.

00:02:20.874 --> 00:02:22.776 align:middle line:90%
So it was totally new for me.

00:02:22.776 --> 00:02:30.417 align:middle line:84%
But I was a young doctor and
specializing and only until '86,

00:02:30.417 --> 00:02:32.620 align:middle line:84%
I read the first book
about near-death experience

00:02:32.620 --> 00:02:35.522 align:middle line:84%
by George Ritchie,
"Return From Tomorrow"

00:02:35.522 --> 00:02:37.725 align:middle line:84%
where he describes his
near-death experience

00:02:37.725 --> 00:02:41.495 align:middle line:84%
as a medical student
in '43 where he died

00:02:41.495 --> 00:02:44.231 align:middle line:84%
of double pneumonia and he
didn't get any antibiotics

00:02:44.231 --> 00:02:45.833 align:middle line:84%
because they were
not available yet.

00:02:45.833 --> 00:02:49.670 align:middle line:84%
So he died and he
was resuscitated.

00:02:49.670 --> 00:02:51.672 align:middle line:90%
Because of the nurse, he was--

00:02:51.672 --> 00:02:55.376 align:middle line:84%
his corpse was just
covered by a blanket.

00:02:55.376 --> 00:02:58.112 align:middle line:90%
And a nurse that was so--

00:02:58.112 --> 00:03:00.447 align:middle line:84%
didn't accepted this
young medical student died

00:03:00.447 --> 00:03:03.617 align:middle line:84%
so he persuaded the doctor
to give an injection right

00:03:03.617 --> 00:03:06.520 align:middle line:84%
into his heart, what was
quite uncommon in '43

00:03:06.520 --> 00:03:09.857 align:middle line:84%
but he regained consciousness
after nine minutes,

00:03:09.857 --> 00:03:13.661 align:middle line:84%
then had an extremely
extensive near-death experience.

00:03:13.661 --> 00:03:15.763 align:middle line:90%
And as a medical doctor, he told

00:03:15.763 --> 00:03:18.332 align:middle line:84%
about this experience
at college.

00:03:18.332 --> 00:03:21.502 align:middle line:84%
And one of the medical
students was Raymond Moody.

00:03:21.502 --> 00:03:25.039 align:middle line:84%
So Raymond Moody was inspired by
this man as well and he started

00:03:25.039 --> 00:03:27.441 align:middle line:84%
to do these studies about
near-death experience

00:03:27.441 --> 00:03:30.678 align:middle line:84%
and his book "Life After
Life" was published in '75

00:03:30.678 --> 00:03:33.447 align:middle line:84%
but I didn't read it,
I didn't know about it.

00:03:33.447 --> 00:03:36.949 align:middle line:84%
So when I read this book of--
by George Ritchie in '86,

00:03:36.949 --> 00:03:39.386 align:middle line:84%
I just started to
interview my patients to ask

00:03:39.386 --> 00:03:41.655 align:middle line:84%
if they could remember
something from the period

00:03:41.655 --> 00:03:43.791 align:middle line:84%
of cardiac arrest, from the
period of unconsciousness.

00:03:43.791 --> 00:03:46.327 align:middle line:84%
>> But what made that switch
because it's quite impressive

00:03:46.327 --> 00:03:49.496 align:middle line:84%
from the moment you were 0:03:48
before or at least, very,

00:03:49.496 --> 00:03:53.133 align:middle line:84%
in the scientific world, very
rigorous, very analytical

00:03:53.133 --> 00:03:55.636 align:middle line:84%
and there is something--
people, I guess,

00:03:55.636 --> 00:03:57.871 align:middle line:84%
a lot of people were starting
to report it more and more

00:03:57.871 --> 00:04:01.442 align:middle line:84%
but what-- like at some point,
there must have been something.

00:04:01.442 --> 00:04:04.978 align:middle line:84%
>> Well, for me it was
scientific curiosity

00:04:04.978 --> 00:04:06.780 align:middle line:84%
because it was totally
impossible

00:04:06.780 --> 00:04:08.816 align:middle line:84%
that patients could
have memories

00:04:08.816 --> 00:04:10.351 align:middle line:84%
from the periods
of unconsciousness.

00:04:10.351 --> 00:04:13.120 align:middle line:84%
So, when I started to
ask patients in '86,

00:04:13.120 --> 00:04:15.656 align:middle line:84%
within two years,
out of 50 patients

00:04:15.656 --> 00:04:17.690 align:middle line:84%
who had survived a
cardiac arrest in the past,

00:04:17.690 --> 00:04:21.595 align:middle line:90%
12 patients told me about NDE.

00:04:21.595 --> 00:04:25.232 align:middle line:84%
And that was the moment that I
said, "Well, until that part,

00:04:25.232 --> 00:04:28.335 align:middle line:84%
there had only been
retrospective studies

00:04:28.335 --> 00:04:32.940 align:middle line:84%
and they all have-- were
very selective for what kind

00:04:32.940 --> 00:04:34.875 align:middle line:90%
of patients they included.

00:04:34.875 --> 00:04:39.179 align:middle line:84%
And it was impossible to find
the medical circumstances

00:04:39.179 --> 00:04:42.082 align:middle line:84%
exactly back after
20 or 30 years.

00:04:42.082 --> 00:04:44.451 align:middle line:84%
So there were no,
until that time,

00:04:44.451 --> 00:04:48.422 align:middle line:84%
no really well-done
scientific studies

00:04:48.422 --> 00:04:52.559 align:middle line:84%
and there had been a series
that this kind of experiences,

00:04:52.559 --> 00:04:55.562 align:middle line:84%
the near-death experience
were caused by lack of oxygen

00:04:55.562 --> 00:04:58.098 align:middle line:84%
in the brain or just
had a sedation--

00:04:58.098 --> 00:05:03.270 align:middle line:84%
side effect of drugs
or dreams or whatever.

00:05:03.270 --> 00:05:06.673 align:middle line:84%
But I couldn't believe
it, but the main thing was

00:05:06.673 --> 00:05:10.778 align:middle line:84%
that I was raised as an
old fashioned academic

00:05:10.778 --> 00:05:15.749 align:middle line:84%
and had learned that there's
always a materialistic

00:05:15.749 --> 00:05:20.120 align:middle line:84%
explanation for things we
see and I always accepted

00:05:20.120 --> 00:05:23.190 align:middle line:84%
that consciousness is just
a product of brain function.

00:05:23.190 --> 00:05:25.025 align:middle line:84%
But now when you
hear patients tell

00:05:25.025 --> 00:05:27.728 align:middle line:84%
about this enhanced
consciousness during cardiac

00:05:27.728 --> 00:05:31.965 align:middle line:84%
arrest, then the question
come, "How is it possible?"

00:05:31.965 --> 00:05:34.267 align:middle line:84%
because when consciousness
should be a product

00:05:34.267 --> 00:05:38.439 align:middle line:84%
of brain function, then they
shouldn't have any memory at all

00:05:38.439 --> 00:05:40.908 align:middle line:84%
from those period
of cardiac arrest.

00:05:40.908 --> 00:05:43.477 align:middle line:90%
So then we started in '88

00:05:43.477 --> 00:05:46.447 align:middle line:84%
in ten Dutch hospitals a
prospective study in all--

00:05:46.447 --> 00:05:53.687 align:middle line:84%
in 344 consecutive patients who
survived cardiac arrest, and--

00:05:53.687 --> 00:05:56.590 align:middle line:84%
which means that we asked
patients within several days

00:05:56.590 --> 00:06:00.360 align:middle line:84%
after resuscitation if they
could remember something

00:06:00.360 --> 00:06:01.862 align:middle line:90%
from the period

00:06:01.862 --> 00:06:03.497 align:middle line:84%
of unconsciousness
and they recalled.

00:06:03.497 --> 00:06:06.133 align:middle line:84%
And patients [inaudible] cardiac
arrest are called clinical

00:06:06.133 --> 00:06:09.436 align:middle line:84%
deaths which means
they are unconscious

00:06:09.436 --> 00:06:14.541 align:middle line:84%
because of no circulation,
no breathing, because of lack

00:06:14.541 --> 00:06:16.043 align:middle line:90%
of oxygen in the brain.

00:06:16.043 --> 00:06:18.779 align:middle line:84%
>> Is that what we
called commonly a coma?

00:06:18.779 --> 00:06:21.782 align:middle line:84%
>> It's a kind of coma
but coma is meant by--

00:06:21.782 --> 00:06:25.619 align:middle line:90%
mostly by a direct brain damage.

00:06:25.619 --> 00:06:30.057 align:middle line:84%
But I call it clinical death
because this is the first stage

00:06:30.057 --> 00:06:34.294 align:middle line:84%
of the process of dying and you
have to resuscitate within five

00:06:34.294 --> 00:06:37.030 align:middle line:84%
to 10 minutes, otherwise
people will die

00:06:37.030 --> 00:06:39.032 align:middle line:84%
because of irreversible
damage to the brain.

00:06:39.032 --> 00:06:42.536 align:middle line:90%
So we have to be very fast.

00:06:42.536 --> 00:06:49.076 align:middle line:84%
At this time, the irreversible
period of unconsciousness.

00:06:49.076 --> 00:06:53.480 align:middle line:84%
But we know from other
studies that these patients--

00:06:53.480 --> 00:06:56.383 align:middle line:84%
and we also note from
the clinical findings

00:06:56.383 --> 00:06:59.286 align:middle line:84%
within seconds patients
become unconscious

00:06:59.286 --> 00:07:01.355 align:middle line:90%
when the heart stops.

00:07:01.355 --> 00:07:04.691 align:middle line:84%
And-- but you mentioned
the blood flow

00:07:04.691 --> 00:07:06.827 align:middle line:84%
through the carotid
arteries, the blood flows

00:07:06.827 --> 00:07:08.395 align:middle line:84%
to zero [phonetic]
within one second.

00:07:08.395 --> 00:07:11.064 align:middle line:84%
There's no blood
going to the brain.

00:07:11.064 --> 00:07:14.735 align:middle line:84%
And there are no body reflexes
anymore which is a function

00:07:14.735 --> 00:07:17.004 align:middle line:90%
of the cortex of the brain.

00:07:17.004 --> 00:07:20.908 align:middle line:84%
There are no brain-- brainstem
reflexes anymore, the gag reflex

00:07:20.908 --> 00:07:23.911 align:middle line:84%
or corneal reflex of
why don't pupils do--

00:07:23.911 --> 00:07:26.380 align:middle line:90%
don't react to light anymore.

00:07:26.380 --> 00:07:27.881 align:middle line:90%
So the brain affects that.

00:07:27.881 --> 00:07:29.383 align:middle line:90%
The breathing has [inaudible].

00:07:29.383 --> 00:07:31.451 align:middle line:84%
The breathing center is
closest to the brainstem.

00:07:31.451 --> 00:07:34.788 align:middle line:84%
So we know those patients
have no brain function

00:07:34.788 --> 00:07:36.323 align:middle line:90%
at all within seconds.

00:07:36.323 --> 00:07:39.459 align:middle line:84%
And when-- there had been
studies done in animals and also

00:07:39.459 --> 00:07:43.730 align:middle line:84%
in humans with the
registration of electroactivity

00:07:43.730 --> 00:07:46.867 align:middle line:90%
of the cortex, the EEG.

00:07:46.867 --> 00:07:51.071 align:middle line:84%
And EEG is flat line
in 15 seconds.

00:07:51.071 --> 00:07:54.541 align:middle line:84%
So we know the clinical findings
and the measurements we can do

00:07:54.541 --> 00:07:57.344 align:middle line:84%
for the electroactivity
of the brain,

00:07:57.344 --> 00:07:58.845 align:middle line:90%
there's no activity at all.

00:07:58.845 --> 00:08:01.081 align:middle line:84%
There's no brain
function at all.

00:08:01.081 --> 00:08:05.385 align:middle line:84%
And in this period, people can
have enhanced consciousness

00:08:05.385 --> 00:08:10.090 align:middle line:84%
with self-identity, with
cognition, with memories

00:08:10.090 --> 00:08:14.194 align:middle line:84%
from early childhood, with
meeting of deceased relatives,

00:08:14.194 --> 00:08:16.430 align:middle line:84%
with the possibility of
perception, from a position out

00:08:16.430 --> 00:08:21.702 align:middle line:84%
or above the body, with
conscious return into the body

00:08:21.702 --> 00:08:25.272 align:middle line:90%
as well which is awful for them.

00:08:25.272 --> 00:08:27.541 align:middle line:90%
And, so what we tried to find

00:08:27.541 --> 00:08:31.011 align:middle line:84%
out if there could be an
explanation why people can have

00:08:31.011 --> 00:08:34.247 align:middle line:84%
this enhanced consciousness
because according

00:08:34.247 --> 00:08:36.717 align:middle line:84%
to our current medical
consult, it's not possible

00:08:36.717 --> 00:08:40.454 align:middle line:84%
because when the-- consciousness
is a product of brain function

00:08:40.454 --> 00:08:42.888 align:middle line:84%
and the brain functions
[inaudible] there shouldn't be

00:08:42.888 --> 00:08:44.391 align:middle line:90%
no consciousness at all.

00:08:44.391 --> 00:08:47.427 align:middle line:84%
So what we found in
this prospective study

00:08:47.427 --> 00:08:49.062 align:middle line:84%
which is still the
largest study ever--

00:08:49.062 --> 00:08:51.164 align:middle line:84%
prospective study even
done and the only study

00:08:51.164 --> 00:08:57.671 align:middle line:84%
with statistical analysis,
what we found that 18 percent

00:08:57.671 --> 00:09:02.209 align:middle line:84%
of the patients, 62 patients had
a clear memory of the periods

00:09:02.209 --> 00:09:04.678 align:middle line:84%
of unconsciousness having
near-death experience.

00:09:04.678 --> 00:09:08.682 align:middle line:84%
And 82 percent did not
have any memory at all.

00:09:08.682 --> 00:09:12.719 align:middle line:84%
And then when we compared
these two groups of patients,

00:09:12.719 --> 00:09:14.788 align:middle line:90%
there was no difference at all.

00:09:14.788 --> 00:09:17.457 align:middle line:84%
So the duration of cardiac
arrest if it was two minutes

00:09:17.457 --> 00:09:18.992 align:middle line:84%
or eight minutes
didn't matter at all.

00:09:18.992 --> 00:09:23.530 align:middle line:84%
Also the severity of anoxia
of the brain, lack of oxygen

00:09:23.530 --> 00:09:25.032 align:middle line:84%
in the brain didn't
matter at all.

00:09:25.032 --> 00:09:28.502 align:middle line:84%
If they had been unconscious for
five minutes or for three weeks

00:09:28.502 --> 00:09:30.704 align:middle line:90%
in coma didn't matter at all.

00:09:30.704 --> 00:09:32.806 align:middle line:84%
If you have an induced
cardiac arrest

00:09:32.806 --> 00:09:35.175 align:middle line:84%
and electrophysiologic
stimulation studies

00:09:35.175 --> 00:09:38.645 align:middle line:84%
in the [inaudible],
they're always resuscitated

00:09:38.645 --> 00:09:42.049 align:middle line:84%
within 30 seconds,
didn't matter at all.

00:09:42.049 --> 00:09:44.918 align:middle line:90%
If they have pre-knowledge

00:09:44.918 --> 00:09:48.455 align:middle line:84%
that you know these experiences
are possible didn't matter

00:09:48.455 --> 00:09:49.956 align:middle line:90%
at all.

00:09:49.956 --> 00:09:51.625 align:middle line:84%
The different medication--
you give a lot of medication

00:09:51.625 --> 00:09:54.928 align:middle line:84%
but people are in coma
or have a complicated CPR

00:09:54.928 --> 00:09:57.164 align:middle line:90%
where they need intubation,

00:09:57.164 --> 00:10:00.434 align:middle line:84%
artificial respiration,
didn't matter at all.

00:10:00.434 --> 00:10:05.872 align:middle line:84%
Gender, religion, education,
didn't matter at all.

00:10:05.872 --> 00:10:11.111 align:middle line:84%
So what we found is that there
is no scientific explanation why

00:10:11.111 --> 00:10:13.680 align:middle line:84%
patients have this
kind of experience.

00:10:13.680 --> 00:10:17.617 align:middle line:84%
We could exclude psychological
explanation like fear

00:10:17.617 --> 00:10:20.320 align:middle line:84%
of death before the
arrest most of the case,

00:10:20.320 --> 00:10:23.190 align:middle line:84%
pharmacological explanation,
there's the side effects

00:10:23.190 --> 00:10:27.461 align:middle line:84%
of drugs, and we could exclude
physiological explanation,

00:10:27.461 --> 00:10:29.996 align:middle line:84%
lack of oxygen to the brain
but because all patients

00:10:29.996 --> 00:10:31.698 align:middle line:84%
of our study had
been unconscious

00:10:31.698 --> 00:10:33.400 align:middle line:90%
because of lack of oxygen.

00:10:33.400 --> 00:10:37.504 align:middle line:84%
Now, the 80 percent of those
patients reported an NDE.

00:10:37.504 --> 00:10:40.707 align:middle line:84%
So that was the first part of
the study, the prospective part

00:10:40.707 --> 00:10:44.244 align:middle line:84%
but we could exclude
all until that now--

00:10:44.244 --> 00:10:49.716 align:middle line:84%
that point, assumptions that
is experienced would be caused

00:10:49.716 --> 00:10:52.719 align:middle line:84%
by anoxia or by hallucinations
or whatever.

00:10:52.719 --> 00:10:54.421 align:middle line:90%
We could exclude it.

00:10:54.421 --> 00:10:55.989 align:middle line:84%
And the second part
of the study,

00:10:55.989 --> 00:10:58.191 align:middle line:84%
what we did was a
longitudinal study

00:10:58.191 --> 00:11:00.827 align:middle line:84%
where we interviewed all
survivors of cardiac arrest

00:11:00.827 --> 00:11:05.532 align:middle line:84%
to visit NDE after two
years and after eight years,

00:11:05.532 --> 00:11:07.334 align:middle line:84%
with a matched control
group of patients,

00:11:07.334 --> 00:11:11.238 align:middle line:84%
we had also survived cardiac
arrest with no memories at all.

00:11:11.238 --> 00:11:12.739 align:middle line:90%
And we did this study,

00:11:12.739 --> 00:11:15.442 align:middle line:84%
it was also the first
longitudinal study

00:11:15.442 --> 00:11:17.210 align:middle line:90%
with prospective design to see

